The Speaker in the United States, by tradition, is the head of the majority party in the House of Representatives, outranking the Majority Leader.

While the Speaker is the functioning head of the House majority party, the same is not true of the President pro tempore of the Senate, whose office is primarily ceremonial and honorary.

When the Speaker and the President belong to the same party, the Speaker normally plays a less prominent role as the leader of the majority party.

The Speaker is the highest-ranking member of the opposition party and is normally the chief public opponent of the President's agenda.

The Speaker holds a variety of powers as the presiding officer of the House of Representatives, but usually delegates them to another member of the majority party.

